* ============================================================
*  PINOCCHIO NAV FILTER + BOUNDARY REGRESSION
*
*  Status:  CANDIDATE / REVIEW_BEFORE_EXECUTION. READ-ONLY (no mutation).
*  Purpose: Exercise the parts of the nav fix the endpoint/skip proof did not:
*             - filtered TOP/BOTTOM/SKIP (the streaming logical_nav path)
*             - empty-result filter (graceful, no crash)
*             - unfiltered SKIP across an order boundary (the fast cursor path,
*               all-or-nothing, no cache build)
*
*  NOTES ON EXPECTED COST
*  ----------------------
*  Filtered TOP/BOTTOM/SKIP stream the index cursor and test each candidate with
*  the same visibility gate LIST/COUNT use, stopping at the first visible row.
*  That is O(distance to the nearest visible row), NOT O(1): a filter that
*  matches nothing costs a full scan by design. This is inherent to filtering
*  without a filtered index -- it is not a regression, and it is the same gate
*  the rest of the engine uses. Unfiltered SKIP (Section F) uses the O(log n)
*  cursor step and stays in the millisecond range.
*
*  RUN
*  ---
*  DOTSCRIPT TRACE scripts\pinocchio\pinocchio_nav_filter_boundary.dts OUT tmp\pinocchio\filter_boundary.log
* ============================================================
SET ECHO OFF
SET TIMER ON
SET TALK ON

SET PATH DBF DBF/pinocchio
SET PATH INDEXES INDEXES/pinocchio
SET PATH LMDB LMDB/pinocchio

* ============================================================
* SECTION E -- filtered navigation (LogicalView / streaming path)
* ============================================================
ECHO === E0. open STUDENTS, order by SID ===
SELECT 0
USE STUDENTS
SET INDEX TO STUDENTS
SET ORDER TO TAG SID

ECHO === E1. dense char filter LNAME = "Anderson" ===
SET FILTER TO LNAME = "Anderson"
COUNT
ECHO --- E1a. filtered TOP: first visible Anderson in SID order (DISPLAY confirms LNAME) ---
TOP
DISPLAY
ECHO --- E1b. SKIP forward stays within the filter (each landing is an Anderson) ---
SKIP
DISPLAY
SKIP
DISPLAY
ECHO --- E1c. filtered BOTTOM: last visible Anderson in SID order ---
BOTTOM
DISPLAY
ECHO --- E1d. SKIP +1 past the last visible row -> at end (no move) ---
SKIP
ECHO --- E1e. filtered TOP then SKIP -1 -> at top (no move) ---
TOP
SKIP -1
SET FILTER TO

ECHO === E2. descending + filter: endpoints swap ===
SET FILTER TO LNAME = "Anderson"
DESCEND
ECHO --- E2a. descending filtered TOP == ascending filtered BOTTOM ---
TOP
DISPLAY
ECHO --- E2b. descending filtered BOTTOM == ascending filtered TOP ---
BOTTOM
DISPLAY
ASCEND
SET FILTER TO

ECHO === E3. empty-result filter -> graceful, no crash (full-scan cost is expected) ===
SET FILTER TO SID = 99999999
COUNT
ECHO --- E3a. filtered TOP with no visible row -> nav reports end, no move ---
TOP
ECHO --- E3b. filtered BOTTOM with no visible row -> nav reports end, no move ---
BOTTOM
SET FILTER TO

* ============================================================
* SECTION F -- unfiltered SKIP across boundaries (fast cursor path)
* ============================================================
ECHO === F0. open ENROLL (5.5M), order by SID ===
SELECT 1
USE ENROLL
SET INDEX TO ENROLL
SET ORDER TO TAG SID

ECHO === F1. BOTTOM then SKIP +1 -> at end (no move, no cache build) ===
BOTTOM
SKIP
ECHO === F2. TOP then SKIP -1 -> at top (no move) ===
TOP
SKIP -1
ECHO === F3. large in-range SKIP out and back (should round-trip to the same recno) ===
TOP
SKIP 1000000
SKIP -1000000
ECHO === F4. partial-to-boundary: near an end, an overshoot SKIP stops at the end ===
BOTTOM
SKIP -5
SKIP 100
SKIP -1000000000

ECHO ============================================================
ECHO FILTER + BOUNDARY REGRESSION COMPLETE. Confirm:
ECHO   E1: COUNT = number of Andersons; every DISPLAY after TOP/SKIP/BOTTOM
ECHO       shows LNAME = Anderson; SKIP past each end reports "at end"/"at top".
ECHO   E2: descending TOP == ascending BOTTOM recno, and vice versa.
ECHO   E3: COUNT = 0; TOP/BOTTOM report no movement, no crash.
ECHO   F1/F2: SKIP past BOTTOM/TOP reports end/top in milliseconds (cursor path,
ECHO          NOT a multi-second cache build).
ECHO   F3: SKIP 1000000 (recno 1000001) then SKIP -1000000 returns to recno 1,
ECHO       both in well under a second (one seek + N cursor advances, no re-seek).
ECHO   F4: SKIP 100 from recno 5501353 stops at 5501358 (partial-to-end); the
ECHO       huge negative SKIP walks back to recno 1 quickly.
ECHO ============================================================
